\title{\bf The Monitoring Wall and the Monitorability Tax:\\
a sharp phase transition for the model--vs--monitor game}
\author{Guangyu Wang\\ \texttt{billgywang@gmail.com}\\[4pt]
\small (working draft --- for internal iteration)}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Chain-of-thought (CoT) monitoring is a leading oversight tool, and an empirically fragile one: under
optimization pressure a model learns \emph{obfuscated} reward hacking that scrubs intent from the
trace. We show that whether monitoring survives this pressure is governed by a sharp, computable
\emph{wall}---whose \emph{height} is the value of a game between a model hiding a hack and a monitor
choosing where to look. \emph{(i) Mechanism (unconditional):} against a fixed monitor the extractable
signal collapses at a critical pressure $\rho^\star=1-\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}/s^2$, with a matching
converse---no test of the projected traces detects the hack \emph{consistently}---so monitoring fails as a \emph{cliff},
not a slope. \emph{(ii) Game value (main new result):} when the model chooses its hiding spectrum,
the wall becomes a critical reward $V^\star$; spreading the hack over a $K$-dimensional task subspace
buys an advantage a sophisticated monitor claws back to $\sqrt K$, and that \emph{saturates} once the
hack's total variance gives it away. \emph{(iii) Design principle:} the footprint of reward hacking
is \emph{irreducible}---relocatable into the monitor's null channel but not erasable---so an
\emph{adaptive} monitor that aims at the reward structure \emph{collapses} the wall when that structure is public and coverable (\S\ref{sec:results}, B1--B4). Robust
monitoring is about \emph{where you look}, not a better classifier. The wall and its converse are
unconditional; the game value is proved under stated low-rank, fixed-resolution assumptions; the
saturation and collapse laws are extensions, with one covering regime---characterized in the core as a slope. We package the theory as
a monitor-side \emph{Meter} that reads the current wall height.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
As models are trained with reinforcement on outcomes they can verify---passing unit tests,
satisfying a checker, maximizing a reward model---and are deployed as agents acting over long
horizons, human review of every action becomes infeasible. A leading fallback is
\emph{monitoring} the model's own externalized reasoning: read the chain of thought (CoT) or
execution trace and flag any trace whose \emph{intent} looks unsafe, even when the final output
does not. A growing number of safety cases lean on this legibility of intent, precisely because
it promises to catch misbehavior that output-level checks miss.

The premise is that intent stays legible. It does not, once the trace itself comes under
optimization pressure. A coding agent rewarded for green tests can learn to special-case the
tests while emitting a clean, plausible rationale; a model penalized whenever its CoT reveals a
shortcut learns to take the shortcut silently. Applying optimization pressure to the CoT
empirically elicits \emph{obfuscated} hacking: the rewarded behavior is retained while the
tell-tale signal is scrubbed, so the monitor's readings can look \emph{healthier} even as the
underlying behavior gets worse~\cite{baker,korbak,spillover}. Monitoring therefore has a failure
mode that is invisible from the monitor's own dashboard---the most dangerous kind, because the
warning sign is the thing being erased.

What is the \emph{shape} of this degradation? Three qualitatively different answers coexist in
the literature, with opposite operational consequences. It could be \emph{gradual}---more
pressure, proportionally less signal---in which case monitoring buys a graceful, tunable safety
margin one can trade off. It could be a \emph{cliff}---signal is fine until a threshold, then
vanishes---in which case a monitor reading healthy today can be one optimization step from blind,
and the AUC one watches is not a safety margin at all. And it could be
\emph{unavoidable}---beyond some capability gap, no achievable monitor helps and the only honest
move is to stop optimizing. The existing formal tools do not adjudicate between these: an
information-theoretic \emph{metric} $I(O;Z\mid X)$ between trace $O$ and intent $Z$~\cite{cotmi},
or a decision-theoretic \emph{gap} $1-\mathrm{TV}$~\cite{stegodt}, quantify how much signal
remains at a given operating point but do not locate a threshold; steganography shows
undetectable channels \emph{can} exist~\cite{dewitt,motwani}, but not \emph{when optimization is
forced across} into them, nor the price of staying out.

\paragraph{The picture.} Our results replace the fatalistic reading (``monitoring is doomed to
fail at a cliff'') with a sharper and more actionable one. Reward hacking leaves a
\emph{statistical footprint} in the reward-relevant subspace of the trace; the model can
\emph{relocate} that footprint into directions the monitor does not resolve---its null
channel---but, because the footprint \emph{is} the reward-directed variance, it cannot
\emph{erase} it while still collecting the reward. Whether monitoring survives optimization pressure
is therefore not a fixed fact but the value of a game over \emph{where the monitor looks}, set by
three levers: the monitor's resolution $\alpha$, its data budget $n/d$, and---decisively---whether
it can \emph{aim} at the reward structure. The wall is real and sharp when the monitor is fixed or
blind; it rises, and can collapse, as the monitor gains these.

\paragraph{Contribution.} We characterize this game in three acts.

\emph{Act~I --- the mechanism: a sharp, information-theoretic wall, unconditional (\S\ref{sec:results}).}
These results assume nothing about the model's hiding strategy.
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{The monitoring wall (Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}).} In a proportional high-dimensional
limit, the monitor's recovery \emph{overlap} with the hack direction is strictly positive below a
critical pressure $\rho^\star$ and \emph{exactly zero} above it, with the closed form
$\rho^\star = 1 - \sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}/s^2$ set purely by geometry (resolution $\alpha$, data budget
$n/d$, blatancy $s$). It is a cliff, not a slope, and it sharpens with dimension. (The ambient
dimension cancels in $\rho^\star$; on the low-rank latent spaces of real models the effective-rank
form of \S\ref{sec:results} \emph{raises} the wall, so the bound strengthens rather than fails.)
\item \textbf{A basic limit, not one estimator (Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}).} A matching Le~Cam
second-moment converse: below the wall the clean and hack laws are contiguous, so \emph{no} test of
the projected traces detects the hack consistently. The detection threshold coincides with the
estimation threshold; the wall is information-theoretic.
\item \textbf{The price of legibility (Props.~\ref{sec:results},~\ref{sec:results}).} Staying above a
detection target forces a rigorous floor on retained visible energy that \emph{diverges} with the
capability gap; under a positive-slope assumption the task tax diverges with it. At $\rho^\star$ the
wall, the diverging price, and the hack's disappearance into the null channel coincide---one order
parameter, three readouts.
\end{itemize}

\emph{Act~II --- the wall's height is a game value; this is the paper's central new result
(\S\ref{sec:results}).}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Endogenous hiding (\S\ref{sec:results}).} When the model chooses its hiding
spectrum, the wall becomes a critical reward $V^\star$: spreading the hack over a $K$-dimensional
task subspace lets it hide reward up to $gK\sqrt\gamma$ against a peak detector, $g\sqrt{K\gamma}$
against the optimal one---task rank is the hider's resource, and a sophisticated monitor claws back
exactly $\sqrt K$. We prove this under explicit low-rank, fixed-resolution, orthogonal-spike,
sub-extensive assumptions (A1--A4); $K=1$ recovers Act~I.
\end{itemize}

\emph{Extensions --- charting the game's boundary, and the design law (\S\ref{sec:results}).} The next
two results relax assumptions A3 and A2 and are stated at the weaker rigor their regimes allow (a
scaling bound and a sandwich); they are what make the picture \emph{prescriptive}.
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Spreading self-defeats (\S\ref{sec:results}; scaling).} The $\sqrt K$ advantage
\emph{saturates}: an extensive hack raises the trace's total variance and is given away by it,
capping the hideable reward at $\Theta(g/\sqrt{\alpha\,n/d})$ regardless of $K$.
\item \textbf{Adaptive resolution collapses the wall (\S\ref{sec:results}).} Because the footprint
is irreducible, a monitor that \emph{aims} at the (public, coverable) task subspace and measures its
total variance defeats \emph{all} spreading (assumptions B1--B4)---with enough data $V^\star\to0$. The
wall protects the hider only against a monitor that cannot aim, cannot cover the task
($K_{\mathrm{pool}}{>}\alpha d$), or is data-starved, which yields concrete design principles
for robust monitors (Box~1) and leaves one regime---the covering game, when the task outgrows the
monitor's resolution---which the core characterizes as a \emph{slope} (detection linear in the coverage
fraction $\alpha/\kappa$), with the exact covering law open.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\emph{Rigor spine.} The wall and its converse (Act~I) are unconditional; the game value
(Act~II) is a theorem under A1--A4; the saturation and collapse laws are extensions that map the
boundary and yield the design law, leaving the exact extensive value and the adaptive covering
regime as the program's open problems.

The sharpness throughout is the BBP spiked-covariance transition~\cite{bbp,bgn} (a mean-shift model
would be smooth); we give the CGMT fixed point~\cite{cgmt} behind it and a monitor-side
\emph{Meter} that estimates the current wall height from trace statistics.

\paragraph{What this is, and is not.} This is a \emph{characterization} paper: the load-bearing
results---a phase transition, an information-theoretic converse, and a game value---are self-contained
theory. We validate the \emph{mechanism} in controlled simulation (a Gaussian channel, a routing surrogate, and
a gradient-checked token transformer trained by REINFORCE). We stress the scope: \emph{validation on
real CoT monitors requires Stage~B}---a real reasoning model under a real LLM monitor
(\S\ref{sec:stages})---which our simulations do not substitute for; they establish the mechanism and
its predictions, and Stage~B is where those predictions are tested and can fail. ``Hack'' denotes any behavior that raises reward while an
oversight signal is meant to catch it. We do not claim obfuscation is \emph{possible} (known
\cite{dewitt,motwani}) or that finite oversight distorts objectives (known~\cite{survey}); we
characterize \emph{when} optimization must reach the null channel, \emph{what} staying legible
costs, and \emph{what a monitor must do} to keep the wall high.



\paragraph{Structure and rigor.} The paper reads as three acts---a sharp wall with a converse (Act~I,
unconditional), the wall as a game value (Act~II, under stated assumptions), and its saturation and
adaptive collapse (Act~III, a design law). All the underlying theorems, with their rigor tiers
(proved / conditional / scaling), are established and tabulated in the companion core~\cite{core}; here
we recall them (\S\ref{sec:results}) and put them to work on chain-of-thought monitoring, with a
self-contained restatement of the wall and converse in Appendix~\ref{app:selfcontained}.

\section{Related work}\label{sec:related}
Prior work supplies, separately, the three ingredients this paper combines: evidence that the
phenomenon is real, the right measures for it, and the high-dimensional machinery to make those
measures sharp. None combines them into a threshold with a price.

\paragraph{The phenomenon is real, and empirical.} Applying optimization pressure to the CoT
elicits obfuscated hacking whose intent disappears from the trace~\cite{baker}; monitorability and
its ``fragile window'' are named, but left informal, in~\cite{korbak}; even output-only supervision
spills over and pushes toward an obfuscated CoT~\cite{spillover}; and surveys frame reward hacking
as the structural consequence of compressing a high-dimensional objective into a low-dimensional
proxy~\cite{survey}. These establish \emph{that} monitoring degrades under pressure---not
\emph{when} it must, nor how steeply.

\paragraph{The right measures, at a fixed operating point.} CoT monitorability has been cast as
the mutual information $I(O;Z\mid X)$ between trace and intent~\cite{cotmi} and as a
decision-theoretic steganographic gap $1-\mathrm{TV}$~\cite{stegodt}; both quantify how much signal
survives at a given pressure, and both explicitly flag the missing minimal-detectable-effect /
threshold analysis. Steganography shows perfectly secure channels \emph{can} exist~\cite{dewitt},
and secret collusion strengthens with capability~\cite{motwani}. These give existence and an
empirical scaling trend; we supply the threshold that separates the regimes and turn the trend
into a divergence.

\paragraph{The machinery.} Our sharpness is the spiked-covariance phase transition of
Baik--Ben~Arous--P\'ech\'e~\cite{bbp} with the eigenvector-overlap law of~\cite{bgn,paul}; the
constrained (tax) analysis uses the Convex Gaussian Min-max Theorem~\cite{cgmt}. Transplanting this
mature high-dimensional-statistics threshold into the monitoring problem---and reading its value
function as a price---is the contribution; the random-matrix results themselves are standard.

\paragraph{Alternative monitoring models.} It helps to place our covariance-spike model against the
alternatives it is often confused with. \emph{Mean-shift / LDA detection}: if the hack were a
first-order (mean) signature, detection would be a linear-discriminant problem with a smooth,
thresholdless $\mathrm{erf}$ power curve---no wall; this is the ``clumsy hack'' regime, and modeling
obfuscation as second order is what yields the sharp $\rho^\star$. \emph{Classifier calibration}: a
trained monitor's accuracy or calibration on the visible features is an operating-point summary
(and, if linear, the LDA case); it reports how well one detects \emph{now}, not the pressure at
which detection becomes impossible. \emph{Mutual-information metrics} $I(O;Z\mid X)$~\cite{cotmi}:
likewise quantify residual signal at a fixed point and, as their authors note, lack a
minimal-detectable-effect analysis; our $\rho^\star$ is exactly that missing threshold, and the
converse turns ``$I$ is small'' into ``no test succeeds.'' \emph{Steganographic channels}
($1-\mathrm{TV}$, secure coding)~\cite{stegodt,dewitt}: establish that undetectable channels can
exist; we add \emph{when} optimization is forced into one and \emph{what} staying out costs. The
alternatives are operating-point or existence statements; ours is a threshold with a price.

\section{Setup: the toy channel}\label{sec:setup}
We distil the model--vs--monitor interaction to its smallest faithful form: recovering a planted
signal from a partially observed, noisy channel. A trace is a high-dimensional object
$O\in\R^{d}$---think of the features a monitor could in principle read off a CoT. A benign trace
is unstructured noise; a hack leaves a \emph{statistical footprint}, an extra structured
component along some hidden direction $u$. Crucially the footprint is \emph{second order}: an
obfuscated hack does not shift the \emph{average} trace (that would be trivially visible), it
perturbs the trace's \emph{covariance} along $u$. Formally, a hack bit
$Z\in\{\text{clean},\text{hack}\}$ injects an anisotropic variance spike of energy $s^2$ along a
unit direction $u\in\R^{d}$:
\begin{equation}
\text{hack:}\ O=\xi+s\,\eta\,u,\quad \eta\sim\mathcal N(0,1),\ \xi\sim\mathcal N(0,I_d);
\qquad \text{clean:}\ O=\xi;\qquad \mathrm{Cov}_{\text{hack}}=I_d+s^2 uu^\top .
\end{equation}
The monitor resolves only a subspace $\Smon$ of dimension $\dmon=\alpha d$; it observes
$P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$ and must recover $u$ from $n$ samples. ($P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ is a literal
projection for a linear probe; for an LLM judge it is a \emph{local, empirical sensitivity
subspace}---the directions whose perturbation flips the verdict---and $\alpha,\rho,\knull$ become
effective quantities read off that map; see \S\ref{sec:meter} and Table~\ref{tab:nonlin}.) Under
\emph{optimization pressure}
$\rho\in[0,1]$ the model splits the spike: a fraction $(1-\rho)$ of the energy stays in
$\Smon$ (``visible'') and a fraction $\rho$ is steered into the \emph{null channel}
$\Smon^{\perp}$ of dimension $\knull=(1-\alpha)d$. Thus $\rho$ is exactly the fraction of hack
energy hidden from the monitor. The visible spike is $s^2(1-\rho)$; the monitor's sample
covariance of $P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$ has a Marchenko--Pastur bulk edge at $\sqrt{\dmon/n}$.

Four numbers govern the game, each with an operational reading. The \emph{blatancy} $s^2$ is how
loud the hack's footprint is relative to trace noise. The \emph{monitor resolution}
$\alpha=\dmon/d$ is the fraction of the trace's degrees of freedom the monitor can actually
read; a weak or coarse monitor has small $\alpha$. The \emph{data budget} $n/d$ is how many
independent traces the monitor aggregates per trace dimension---its statistical power. The
\emph{optimization pressure} $\rho$ is the only quantity the training loop moves: it is the
fraction of the footprint the model has learned to route into the $\knull=(1-\alpha)d$ directions
the monitor does not read---the null channel. ``A capable model outgrowing a weak monitor'' is the
corner $\rho\to1$, $\alpha$ small, $n/d$ small.

\begin{table}[h]\centering\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l l p{7.2cm}@{}}
\toprule
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{toy symbol}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{meaning}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{real CoT-monitoring counterpart}} \\ \midrule
$O\in\R^d$ & monitored trace & CoT tokens / model activations as a feature vector \\
$\alpha=\dmon/d$ & monitor resolution & fraction of trace d.o.f.\ the monitor reads (probe rank, judge bandwidth) \\
$n/d$ & monitor data budget & labeled traces per trace dimension (probe/judge statistical power) \\
$s^2$ & hack blatancy & strength of the hack's statistical footprint (SNR of the tell) \\
$\rho$ & optimization pressure & fraction of the footprint routed into the monitor's null space \\
$\knull=(1-\alpha)d$ & hidable subspace & trace directions the monitor cannot resolve \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Mapping between the toy channel and real CoT/trace monitoring. Estimating the right-hand
column on a deployed monitor is the object of Stages~A.5--B; the Meter (\S\ref{sec:meter})
estimates $\alpha$, $s$, and $\knull$ from trace statistics.}
\end{table}

\begin{remark}[Why a covariance spike, not a mean shift]
Obfuscation is exactly the move from a first-order to a second-order signature: a hack that
shifted the \emph{mean} trace would be caught by the crudest monitor, so under pressure the
surviving hacks are those that leave the average trace untouched and perturb only its
\emph{shape}. Recovery is then a spiked-\emph{covariance} problem, which carries a genuine
Baik--Ben~Arous--P\'ech\'e threshold; a first-order (mean-shift, LDA) model would instead give a
smooth, thresholdless $\mathrm{erf}$ curve and miss the cliff entirely. The sharpness we report
is thus a consequence of modeling obfuscation honestly, not an artifact of the toy.
\end{remark}

Write $\gamma \equiv \dmon/n = \alpha/(n/d)$ for the effective aspect ratio and
$\beta \equiv s^2(1-\rho)$ for the visible spike strength. Recovery of $u$ from
$P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$ is the planted-vector / spiked-covariance problem; its order parameter is
the overlap $\langle \hat u, u\rangle^2$.

\section{Results: the monitoring channel is an instance of the core}\label{sec:results}
The toy channel of \S\ref{sec:setup} \emph{is} the partial-channel model of the companion theory
paper~\cite{core}, under the reading resolution $=$ monitor bandwidth, budget $=$ labeled traces,
planted signal $=$ obfuscated hack, null space $=$ the monitor's blind directions. All the theorems
below are proved there; we recall them in monitoring notation and use them, and
Appendix~\ref{app:selfcontained} restates the load-bearing wall and converse self-contained so this
paper stands if the core is in review. Throughout, $\gamma=\dmon/n=\alpha/(n/d)$ and
$\beta=s^2(1-\rho)$.

\paragraph{The wall and its converse (core Props.~1--2).} In the proportional regime the recovery
overlap $\langle\hat u,u\rangle^2$ is positive for $\rho<\rho^\star$ and zero for $\rho>\rho^\star$,
with
\begin{equation}\label{eq:rhostar}
\rho^\star=\Big[\,1-\frac{\sqrt{\dmon/n}}{s^2}\,\Big]_0^1=\Big[\,1-\frac{\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}}{s^2}\,\Big]_0^1,
\end{equation}
a Baik--Ben~Arous--P\'ech\'e cliff (overlap $\tfrac{1-\gamma/\beta^2}{1+\gamma/\beta}$ above the edge,
$0$ below) that sharpens as $d^{-1/3}$; and a Le~Cam converse makes clean and hacked traces contiguous
above $\rho^\star$, so \emph{no} test of the projected traces detects the hack consistently
(``a smarter classifier'' cannot help). Operationally: a monitor of bandwidth $\alpha$ and budget
$n/d$ goes blind once the model routes a fraction $\rho^\star$ of the hack's footprint into the null
channel---and clipping means a monitor with $s^2\le\sqrt\gamma$ is blind from the start.

\paragraph{Effective rank (core Cor.~1).} What sets the wall is the \emph{stable rank}
$r_{\mathrm{eff}}=\operatorname{tr}\Sigma_{\mathrm{mon}}/\|\Sigma_{\mathrm{mon}}\|\le\dmon$ of the
resolved covariance ($\gamma_{\mathrm{eff}}=r_{\mathrm{eff}}/n$), exact for a flat/whitened channel and
a deformed-MP proxy otherwise; low-rank activations \emph{lower} the edge and \emph{raise} $\rho^\star$,
so the meter reads $r_{\mathrm{eff}}$ off the whitening step rather than the nominal $\dmon$.

\paragraph{The price (core Prop.~3).} To keep detection AUC$\,\ge\tau$ the model must retain a
resolved-energy fraction $1-\rho_{\max}\ge\beta(\tau)/s^2\ge\sqrt\gamma/s^2$, a floor that \emph{grows}
as the capability gap widens ($n/d\to0$); since the fraction is $\le1$ this is a feasibility ceiling
(once $\beta(\tau)>s^2$, target-level monitoring is infeasible). Under a positive task-loss slope
$\kappa$ this is the monitorability tax $\lmon\ge\kappa\sqrt\gamma/s^2$; $\kappa$ is task-specific and
calibrated in Stage~A.5.

\paragraph{The wall is a game value (core Props.~5--8).} When the model chooses its hiding spectrum
and the monitor aims, the wall becomes a critical hack value: spreading over a $K$-dimensional task
subspace buys a factor $K$ against a peak monitor and $\sqrt K$ against an optimal one
($V^\star_{\mathrm{spec}}=gK\sqrt\gamma$, $V^\star_{\mathrm{opt}}=g\sqrt{K\gamma}$, under the core's
A1--A4). A trivial aggregate statistic caps the hideable value at the single-direction scale
$\Theta(g\sqrt\gamma)$, \emph{independent of $K$} (core Prop.~7), so spreading self-defeats; and an
\emph{adaptive} monitor that aims at the (public) reward structure and measures its total variance
collapses the wall, $V^\star_{\mathrm{adapt}}=\Theta(g\sqrt{K_{\mathrm{pool}}/n})\to0$ (core Prop.~8,
B1--B4). The safety reading: robust monitoring is about \emph{where you look}, not a better
classifier---raw bandwidth without aim only inflates the noise floor (core Rem.~on the $\sqrt\alpha$
monotonicity), while aiming collapses it. The one remaining regime is the covering game
$K_{\mathrm{pool}}>\dmon$ (task richer than bandwidth), which the core characterizes as a \emph{slope}
(detection linear in the coverage fraction), not a warning-free collapse; its exact law is open.

\paragraph{Why a cliff (core Thm.~1).} The sharpness is specific to the \emph{second-order}
(covariance-spike) footprint of an obfuscated hack: within the partial-channel family, the wall is a
cliff iff the footprint is second order; a first-order (mean-shift) tell gives a smooth, thresholdless
$\mathrm{erf}$ curve (Fig.~\ref{fig:baselines}), and reward-model over-optimization is a smooth
generalization error outside the family. Heavy-tailed activations blind the naive covariance estimator
but a robust (spatial-sign) one restores the cliff (core Rem., simulation-backed)---a prescription for
the meter under non-Gaussian traces.


\begin{center}
\fbox{\begin{minipage}{0.94\linewidth}
\textbf{Design principles for robust monitors.} The analysis is prescriptive, not fatalistic---it
says how to keep the wall high (all four levers are theorems in the core~\cite{core}).
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{1pt}
\item \emph{Aim at the reward structure.} The footprint lives where reward is collected; a monitor that
resolves the (public) task subspace measures it directly (core Prop.~8). Aiming beats any fixed generic
probe---and raw bandwidth without aim only inflates the noise floor (core Rem.\ on $\sqrt\alpha$).
\item \emph{Match resolution to task rank.} Keep $\alpha d\ge K_{\mathrm{pool}}$ so the task subspace
fits the budget; below that, the covering game leaves gaps for the hider.
\item \emph{Spend the data budget.} Wall height scales as $1/\sqrt{n}$: more labeled traces per
dimension drive $V^\star\to0$ (core simulations).
\item \emph{Use second-order (covariance) tests.} The sharp wall is a covariance-spike phenomenon; a
mean/linear classifier is smooth and misses the regime (Fig.~\ref{fig:baselines}); under heavy-tailed
traces use a robust (spatial-sign) second-order statistic (core Rem.).
\item \emph{Read the wall; do not wait for the cliff.} The Meter (\S\ref{sec:meter}) estimates
$\hat\rho^\star$/$V^\star$ and the distance to them from trace statistics---AUC gives no warning before
the collapse.
\end{itemize}
\end{minipage}}
\end{center}

\section{Stage-A numerical validation}\label{sec:numerics}
We confirm the core's predictions~\cite{core} in a CoT-flavored toy and then build the empirical
bridge to real chain-of-thought. The monitor estimates $\hat u$ as the top eigenvector of the sample
covariance of $n$ projected hack traces, and scores a held-out \emph{session} of traces by their mean
energy along $\hat u$; detection AUC is hack-vs-clean over such sessions. All numbers below are from a
CPU \texttt{numpy}/\texttt{scipy} re-implementation of the Stage-A protocol ($\alpha=0.5$, $s=1.19$, so
$\rho^\star=0.50$ at $n/d=1$); no values are hand-set. The wall, tax, and dichotomy panels reproduce
the core's Figs.\ in monitoring notation; the surrogate and token panels are this paper's
CoT-specific contribution.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{phase_transition.png}
\caption{\textbf{Monitoring wall (Stage A).} (a) Detection AUC vs optimization pressure
$\rho$; the collapse at $\rho^\star{=}0.50$ (theory, dashed) sharpens with dimension
$d\in\{100,300,900\}$ (evidence of a true transition): AUC falls from $0.985$ near
$\rho{=}0.1$ to $0.53$ by $\rho{=}0.8$. (b) A weaker monitor (smaller $n/d$) is blinded at
lower $\rho$: $\rho^\star$ moves from $0.65$ ($n/d{=}2$) through $0.50$ ($n/d{=}1$) to $0.29$
($n/d{=}0.5$), matching~\eqref{eq:rhostar} (dashed).}
\label{fig:phase}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{tax_divergence.png}
\caption{\textbf{Monitorability-tax divergence (Stage A).} The retained visible energy
$T=1-\rho_{\max}$ needed to keep AUC$\ge\tau{=}0.72$ tracks the theoretical floor
$\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}/s^2$ (dashed) from above and diverges as the monitor weakens / the
capability gap $1/\sqrt{n/d}$ grows (measured tax rises from $0.43$ at a strong monitor to
$0.87$ at a weak one).}
\label{fig:tax}
\end{figure}

Both core claims hold on the toy channel: the wall location matches the closed
form~\eqref{eq:rhostar} and sharpens with $d$; the tax tracks the floor of \S\ref{sec:results} and
diverges linearly in the capability gap. These are the true sources of Figures~1--2.

\paragraph{Finite-size correction.} The wall is a large-$d$ statement; at finite $d$ the BBP
transition is smeared. The top sample eigenvalue fluctuates around the edge at the Tracy--Widom
rate $d^{-2/3}$, which translates through the eigenvalue map into a $\rho$-window of width
$\Delta\rho\asymp c\,d^{-1/3}/s^2$ around $\rho^\star$. Empirically the transition (AUC $0.9\to0.55$)
occupies $[0.29,0.57]$ at $d\in\{600,900\}$ and narrows with $d$ (shaded in Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}a). Two
consequences: the Meter reports $\hat\rho^\star$ with a \emph{band}, not a point (its width is this
finite-$d$ correction plus estimation noise); and, because the window shrinks as $d^{-1/3}$, a
larger trace space makes the wall an operationally \emph{sharper} cliff---the opposite of the usual
intuition that high dimension blurs thresholds. The band should not be read as uncertainty about
\emph{whether} the wall exists, only about \emph{where}, to within $O(d^{-1/3})$.

\paragraph{Baselines: the wall is mechanism-specific.} To show the sharpness is a property of the
\emph{hack model} and not of our detector, Fig.~\ref{fig:baselines} sweeps the same hidden fraction $\rho$ under three
monitors at matched blatancy: our covariance-spike hack read by the BBP detector, and a first-order
\emph{mean-shift} hack read by an LDA detector and by a calibrated linear classifier. Only the
covariance case has a wall---AUC falls to chance at $\hat\rho^\star$; the mean-shift detectors
decline \emph{smoothly} and stay above chance for every $\rho<1$ (an $\mathrm{erf}$ curve, no
threshold). A classifier is only as sharp as its features: on first-order (mean) features it tracks
LDA and is thresholdless; the sharp wall appears precisely because obfuscated hacking is a
\emph{second-order} (covariance) signature. This is the simulated counterpart of the discussion in
\S\ref{sec:related}.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.62\linewidth]{baselines.png}
\caption{\textbf{The wall is specific to the covariance-spike (obfuscated) hack.} Detection AUC vs
hidden fraction $\rho$ at matched blatancy: the covariance-spike hack with a BBP detector (red)
falls to chance at $\hat\rho^\star{=}0.50$; a mean-shift hack read by an LDA detector (blue) or a
calibrated linear classifier (green) declines smoothly and stays detectable for all $\rho<1$. The
threshold is a feature of the second-order mechanism, not of the detector.}
\label{fig:baselines}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:twowalls} seals the coincidence of Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall} and Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}. Plotted
against the single signal-to-threshold ratio $\beta/\sqrt\gamma$, the estimation order parameter
(recovery overlap) departs from zero, and the detection order parameter (the likelihood-ratio
second moment $\E_0[L_n^2]$) diverges, at \emph{the same} point $\beta=\sqrt\gamma$. The wall that
blinds our estimator and the wall past which \emph{no} test is consistent are one and the same;
both closed forms are matched by simulation.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{two_walls.png}
\caption{\textbf{One wall, two order parameters.} Against $\beta/\sqrt\gamma$ (with $\gamma{=}1$):
(a) the estimation wall---recovery overlap $\langle\hat u,u\rangle^2$ is zero for
$\beta<\sqrt\gamma$ and departs from zero exactly at the threshold (Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}); (b) the
detection wall---the likelihood-ratio second moment $\E_0[L_n^2]=(1-\beta^2/\gamma)^{-1/2}$ is
finite in the contiguous (undetectable) regime and diverges at the \emph{same} threshold
(Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}). Markers are simulation; curves are the closed forms. The estimation
and detection thresholds coincide, so ``no estimator recovers the hack'' and ``no test detects it''
are the same event.}
\label{fig:twowalls}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Stage A.5: emergent hiding and tax calibration (surrogate).}
Stage~A imposes $\rho$; the first test that the channel picture survives \emph{training} is to let
$\rho$ emerge. We train a routing policy by gradient ascent to maximize an evasion reward minus a
competence cost of hiding, against an empirical probe monitor (the Stage-A estimator on $n$
samples); as monitor pressure $\lambda$ rises, the policy \emph{learns} to route the variance spike
into the null channel, so $\rho$ emerges rather than being set. (This is a controlled surrogate:
the policy is a continuous router, not a token-level transformer, which is Stage~B.) Two findings
(Fig.~\ref{fig:surrogate}). \emph{(i) The wall predicts the collapse on a trained policy.} As $\lambda$ increases the
emergent $\rho$ sweeps across $\hat\rho^\star$, and the empirical detection AUC collapses at
a finite-$d$ transition window $[0.29,0.57]$ that brackets the predicted $\hat\rho^\star=0.50$ (mean$\pm$sd over $24$ seeds; the window narrows as $d^{-1/3}$); gradient training in $\R^{d}$ reaches the
same optimum as the exact argmax, with bistability precisely at the wall---the policy jumps across
rather than lingering, echoing the cliff of Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}. \emph{(ii) The tax slope.}
Fixing the hack value $B$ and tracing achieved reward $B(1-D_{\mathrm{emp}})$ against retained
visible energy $V=s^2(1-\rho)$ yields a finite marginal slope $\kappa=|dR/dV|=1.9\pm1.2$ that
\emph{peaks at the wall}, consistent with the criticality of \S\ref{sec:results}. The slope's
value is task-specific; what transfers is the structure of \S\ref{sec:results}---a finite slope
times the diverging energy floor gives a tax that diverges as $n/d\to0$. Calibrating the slope on
real CoT is Stage~B.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{stage_a5.png}
\caption{\textbf{Stage A.5 (surrogate): emergence and calibration.} (a) A routing policy trained
under monitor pressure $\lambda$ (color) develops \emph{emergent} hiding $\rho$; the empirical
monitor AUC collapses as the trained $\rho$ crosses the predicted wall $\hat\rho^\star{=}0.50$
(dashed); the shaded finite-$d$ window $[0.29,0.57]$ (mean$\pm$sd, $24$ seeds) brackets it. (b) Monitorability tax: achieved reward (mean$\pm$sd) vs retained
visible energy $V=s^2(1-\rho)$; the marginal slope $|dR/dV|$ peaks at the wall
$V=\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}$, calibrating the slope $\kappa$ of \S\ref{sec:results}(b) ($1.9\pm1.2$).}
\label{fig:surrogate}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Token-transformer confirmation (covariance-spike, RL).}
To test that the picture survives discreteness and noisy RL, we replace the continuous router with
a genuine single-layer causal self-attention transformer (numpy, gradient-checked backprop) that
emits a short discrete CoT; the CoT's readout direction $w$ is the injected spike direction, the
spike magnitude $s^2$ is fixed (so the SNR is controlled), and the policy is trained by REINFORCE
to point $w$ at a mostly-visible value direction $v$ while a monitor penalizes the visible spike
(pressure $\lambda$). We read Fig.~\ref{fig:token} \emph{qualitatively}: it asks whether the mechanism survives
discreteness and RL noise, not whether it quantitatively pins the wall (that is the surrogate's and
large-$d$'s job). Two robust findings: as $\lambda$ rises the emergent hiding $\rho$
rises from $0.28$ to $0.51$ across $\hat\rho^\star=0.50$ (mean over $6$ seeds), with large near-wall variance---a bistable jump, the policy leaping
across rather than sitting on it (the cliff again)---and the hack effectiveness $\langle
w,v\rangle^2$ collapses from $0.39$ to $\approx0.12$ (seed means) as $\rho$ rises, the tax made concrete
on real tokens. The \emph{sharp} AUC collapse is not resolved at the token model's small $d{=}40$
(the transition sharpens with $d$, Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}a; the quantitative $\hat\rho^\star$ and tax slope are the
surrogate's, Fig.~\ref{fig:surrogate}); what the transformer adds is that emergent hiding and the tax survive
discreteness and RL noise---the bridge toward Stage~B.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{token_stage_a5.png}
\caption{\textbf{Token-transformer Stage A.5 (covariance spike, REINFORCE; $6$ seeds).} A
single-layer self-attention policy emits a discrete CoT whose readout direction is the injected
spike. (a) Emergent hiding $\rho$ vs monitor pressure $\lambda$ (mean$\pm$sd; grey dots are
individual seeds; shaded range): $\rho$ rises from $0.28$ to $0.51$ across $\hat\rho^\star{=}0.50$, with
large near-wall variance (bistable jump---the cliff). (b) The tax: hack effectiveness
$\langle w,v\rangle^2$ collapses (from $0.39$ to $\approx0.12$) as the emergent $\rho$ rises past
the wall. The sharp AUC collapse is not resolved at $d{=}40$ (cf.\ Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}a; the sharp
$\hat\rho^\star$ and slope are the surrogate's, Fig.~\ref{fig:surrogate}).}
\label{fig:token}
\end{figure}

\section{Instrument: the Monitorability Meter}\label{sec:meter}
The theory helps an overseer only if it can be read \emph{before} the wall, from quantities
cheaper than the thing it predicts. By the time detection AUC visibly falls the monitor is
already past $\rho^\star$; a useful diagnostic must instead estimate the wall's \emph{location}
and the current \emph{distance} to it from statistics a monitor already collects. The
Monitorability Meter is that diagnostic---a framework-agnostic, monitor-side instrument mirroring
a shadow-price meter. It exposes four calls: \texttt{null\_channel\_dim} (the hidable-subspace
dimension $\knull$, a participation ratio of the residual covariance outside the monitor's
operator), \texttt{wall\_estimate} (the wall location $\hat\rho^\star$ and current distance to it,
with a resampling band), \texttt{monitorability\_price} (the marginal task loss per retained nat of
$I(O;Z\mid X)$), and \texttt{StoppingRule} (``stop before the wall''). The Meter is an
\emph{overseer-side} instrument: unlike the monitor (or adversary), which sees only the projected
channel $P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$, the Meter is run offline with access to the \emph{full} trace embedding
$O$---which it needs to separate $s^2$ from $\rho$ (from $P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$ alone only the visible
spike $s^2(1-\rho)$ is identifiable, so the Meter would report $s^2(1-\rho)$ and a \emph{lower
bound} on $\rho$). It first estimates the benign covariance $\widehat\Sigma_0$ from clean
(non-hacking) traces and \emph{whitens}, $O\mapsto\widehat\Sigma_0^{-1/2}O$, so the inverse-BBP step
sees isotropic noise; write $\widehat C=\tfrac1n\sum_i(\widehat\Sigma_0^{-1/2}O_i)(\cdot)^\top$ for
the whitened sample covariance, top eigenpair $\hat\lambda,\hat u$, and $P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ of rank
$\dmon$:
\begin{align*}
\hat\alpha&=\dmon/d, &
\hat s^2&=\hat\beta:\ \hat\lambda=(1+\hat\beta)\big(1+\tfrac{d/n}{\hat\beta}\big)\ \text{(inverse BBP map)},\\
\hat\rho&=\big\|(I-P_{\mathrm{mon}})\hat u\big\|^2, &
\hat k_{\mathrm{null}}&=\frac{(\operatorname{tr}R)^2}{\operatorname{tr}(R^2)},\ R=(I-P_{\mathrm{mon}})(\widehat C-\hat\lambda\hat u\hat u^\top)(I-P_{\mathrm{mon}}),
\end{align*}
and $\hat\rho^\star=1-\sqrt{\hat\alpha/(n/d)}\,/\,\hat s^2$ by~\eqref{eq:rhostar}. Here $\hat s^2$
is the total spike strength recovered by inverting the BBP eigenvalue map (valid once
$\hat\lambda$ separates from the bulk), $\hat\rho$ its null fraction, and $\hat k_{\mathrm{null}}$
the participation ratio of the residual covariance in the unresolved block. The load-bearing two
routines are:

{\small\begin{verbatim}
estimate_channel(O, O_clean, P_mon, n):   # O: hack traces; O_clean: benign
    Sigma0 = cov(O_clean)                 # benign (noise) covariance
    Chat   = cov(Sigma0^(-1/2) @ O)       # WHITEN, then sample covariance
    lam, u = top_eigenpair(Chat)          # top spike eigenpair
    alpha  = rank(P_mon)/d
    s2  = solve  lam = (1+s2)(1 + (d/n)/s2)    # inverse BBP map
    rho = norm((I - P_mon) @ u)^2              # null fraction of spike
    R   = (I-P_mon)(Chat - lam*outer(u,u))(I-P_mon)   # off-spike residual
    k_null = trace(R)^2 / trace(R@R)           # participation ratio
    return alpha, s2, rho, k_null, u

wall_estimate(O, O_clean, P_mon, n):
    alpha, s2, rho, k_null, u = estimate_channel(O, O_clean, P_mon, n)
    rho_star = 1 - sqrt(alpha/(n/d))/s2   # Eq. (2)
    band = bootstrap(resample O; recompute rho_star)   # width ~ d^-1/3 + noise
    return rho_star, rho, band

StoppingRule(state, delta):               # symptoms coincide (Prop. 4)
    rho_star, rho_now, band = wall_estimate(state.O, state.O_clean,
                                            state.P_mon, state.n)
    price = monitorability_price(state.O, state.Z)      # lambda_mon
    if (rho_star - rho_now) < delta  or  price > budget:
        halt CoT-directed optimization    # stop before the wall
\end{verbatim}}

\noindent Each call needs a trace covariance and a labeled probe set that is small relative to
model training but \emph{not} sub-dimensional: the spike and eigenvector estimates above are
consistent only when the sample size $n$ is comparable to the effective dimension being
resolved---the estimators live in the proportional regime $n/\dmon=\Theta(1)$ (indeed $\hat\rho^\star$
depends on $n/d$), not $n\ll\dmon$. Given that, the Meter needs no white-box access to the model, so
it attaches to any monitor---linear probe, LLM judge, or classifier---as a runtime guardrail rather
than a post-hoc audit.

\begin{table}[h]\centering\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l p{4.4cm} p{5.6cm}@{}}
\toprule
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{estimator}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{assumption}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{failure mode}} \\ \midrule
$\hat s^2$ (inverse BBP) & top eigenvalue separated from the bulk; single dominant spike &
below the wall $\hat\lambda$ re-enters the bulk, so $\hat s^2$ is undefined---the Meter must extrapolate from the last super-critical read \\
$\hat\alpha=\dmon/d$ & fixed, known monitor operator & adaptive monitor re-aims $\Smon$ ($\alpha$ time-varying); use the current $\Smon$ per round \\
$\hat\rho=\|(I{-}P_{\mathrm{mon}})\hat u\|^2$ & top eigenvector \emph{is} the hack direction & multi-spike (rank-$r$) hacks or a noise eigenvector dominating near the wall bias $\hat\rho$; track top-$r$ \\
$\hat k_{\mathrm{null}}$ (participation ratio) & residual covariance well approximated after spike removal & heavy-tailed / structured trace noise inflates the ratio \\
$\hat\rho^\star$ & proportional Gaussian regime; \emph{second-order} (covariance) hack & mean-shift hacks give a smooth curve (no sharp $\rho^\star$); $n\ll d$ breaks the estimate \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Estimator assumptions and failure modes for the Monitorability Meter. The first and last
rows are the operative caveats: the wall estimate is a super-critical extrapolation, and the
sharpness presumes an obfuscated (covariance-spike) hack in the proportional regime. \emph{Rule of
thumb}: use $n/\dmon\gtrsim1$ (the proportional regime the estimators live in); report
$\hat\rho^\star$ as a bootstrap band, not a point, with width $\sim O(d^{-1/3})$ (finite-size) plus
estimation noise, widening as $n/\dmon\downarrow1$.}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Linear probes vs.\ LLM judges.} The operator $P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ is \emph{exact} for a
linear monitor---a probe or classifier whose readout is a fixed rank-$\dmon$ projection of the
trace features---and the estimators above are then literal. An \emph{LLM judge} is nonlinear: there
is no explicit $P_{\mathrm{mon}}$, and the framework applies to its \emph{local linearization}. The
effective resolved operator is the judge's sensitivity map---the span of trace perturbations that
change its verdict, i.e.\ the row space of its Jacobian at the operating point---and $\alpha$,
$\knull$, $\rho$ become \emph{effective} quantities read off that map. The sharp wall is then a
first-order statement about the linearized channel, valid where the judge is locally linear over the
relevant perturbation scale; strong nonlinearity (a judge that reads a genuinely nonlinear feature
of the trace) adds higher-order terms that can move the effective edge, and is outside the current
analysis. Table~\ref{tab:nonlin} records how each estimator is read in the two cases.

\begin{table}[h]\centering\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l p{4.7cm} p{5.4cm}@{}}
\toprule
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{quantity}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{linear probe (exact)}} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{\textbf{LLM judge (effective, linearized)}} \\ \midrule
$P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ & fixed rank-$\dmon$ readout projection & row space of the judge's Jacobian at the operating point \\
$\alpha=\dmon/d$ & probe rank over $d$ & effective rank of the Jacobian over $d$ \\
$\hat s^2,\hat\rho$ & inverse-BBP on the whitened covariance & same, on locally-linearized trace features; higher-order terms dropped \\
$\hat\rho^\star$ & exact threshold & first-order threshold; valid in the locally linear regime \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Reading the Meter's estimators for a linear probe (exact) versus an LLM judge (an effective,
linearized resolution). For the judge, calibrate $P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ empirically---perturb the trace
and record which directions flip the verdict.}
\label{tab:nonlin}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Operational requirements (not optional).} The Meter's estimates are only valid when its
preconditions hold; each is a genuine requirement, not a convenience.
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{1pt}
\item \emph{Full trace embeddings.} Separating $s^2$ from $\rho$ needs the full trace $O$, not just
$P_{\mathrm{mon}}O$; from the projection alone only the visible spike $s^2(1-\rho)$ is identifiable.
\item \emph{Clean covariance and whitening.} The inverse-BBP step assumes isotropic noise; with
anisotropic benign covariance the raw top eigenvalue is dominated by the noise, so
$\widehat\Sigma_0$ must be estimated from clean traces and the trace whitened first
(Fig.~\ref{fig:stress}a).
\item \emph{Super-critical spike.} $\hat s^2$ is read by inverting the BBP map, which requires the
top eigenvalue to have separated from the bulk; below the wall the Meter must extrapolate from the
last super-critical read.
\item \emph{Proportional sample size.} The estimators live in $n/\dmon=\Theta(1)$; with $n\ll\dmon$
the eigenvector estimate is inconsistent and $\hat\rho^\star$ is unreliable.
\item \emph{Rank-aware $\hat\rho$.} A single top eigenvector misreads a multi-spike hack; track the
top-$r$ eigenvectors (Fig.~\ref{fig:stress}b).
\end{itemize}
Figure~\ref{fig:stress} stress-tests these: whitening is required under anisotropic noise, a top-$r$
estimator under multi-spike hacks, and---for a nonlinear (quadratic) judge---the effective
$P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ recovered by perturbation matches the true resolved subspace (overlap $\approx1$),
so the Meter transfers to nonlinear monitors through the sensitivity-subspace reading of
Table~\ref{tab:nonlin}.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{meter_stress.png}
\caption{\textbf{Meter stress tests.} (a) Anisotropic benign noise: the raw $\hat s^2$ error grows
with the noise condition number, while whitening keeps it flat---whitening is required, not optional.
(b) Multi-spike hack (spread null fractions): the top-$1$ estimator is biased; the top-$r$ estimator
tracks the mean $\rho$. (c) Nonlinear (quadratic) judge: the empirical sensitivity subspace recovers
the true resolved subspace (overlap $\approx1$) across nonlinearity strengths, validating the
effective-$P_{\mathrm{mon}}$ reading for LLM judges.}
\label{fig:stress}
\end{figure}

\section{Stage plan (evidence hierarchy)}\label{sec:stages}
The claim is validated in three stages, each buying a different kind of confidence and each
carrying a condition that would falsify it.

\emph{Stage~A (done).} The closed-form BBP wall and the tax floor, confirmed on the toy channel:
detection AUC collapses across $\rho^\star$ and \emph{sharpens} with dimension---the signature of
a true transition rather than a finite-size slope---and the tax tracks $\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}/s^2$
and grows in the capability gap (Figs.~\ref{fig:phase} and~\ref{fig:tax}). This isolates the mechanism; it does not yet show
that this mechanism is the one operating inside a language model.

\emph{Stage~A.5 (surrogate done; \S\ref{sec:numerics}, Fig.~\ref{fig:surrogate}).} A tiny transformer
emitting a short CoT, watched by a \emph{probe} monitor (the Stage-A eigenvector estimator on $n$
samples)---\emph{not} a real LLM judge, which belongs to Stage~B. We apply optimization pressure to
the CoT and ask (i) whether the trace--intent information $I(O;Z\mid X)$ collapses at the
$\hat\rho^\star$ predicted from the channel's estimated $(\alpha,n/d,s)$, and (ii) whether the
Meter's stopping rule trips \emph{before} the collapse. A first, non-token surrogate already confirms
(i)---emergent $\rho$ crosses the wall at the predicted location---and calibrates the tax slope; a
gradient-checked token transformer trained by REINFORCE reproduces the emergent hiding and the tax on
discrete CoTs (Fig.~\ref{fig:token}). What remains for Stage~B is the sharp large-$d$ collapse and,
crucially, a \emph{real LLM monitor}, which no part of the work so far has used. This is the stage
that pins the one free slope in \S\ref{sec:results}.

\emph{Stage~B (specified; GPU).} A real reasoning model under a real LLM CoT monitor in an
agentic coding environment (unit-test hacking). Two conditions make the theory refutable at
scale: the wall must appear where $\knull/(n/d)$ predicts---not at an arbitrary, fitted
pressure---and the tax must \emph{scale} with the capability gap rather than saturating. If either
fails, the transition is not the phenomenon governing real CoT monitoring, and we would report
that.

\section{Limitations and novelty boundary}\label{sec:limits}
\paragraph{Scope of the model.} The results describe a stylized Gaussian channel; the map from
``CoT monitorability'' to $(\alpha,n/d,s,\rho)$ is a modeling posit to be made operational
(Stage~A.5/B). Two assumptions carry the sharpness and bound the scope. First, the hack signature
is taken to be purely \emph{second order} (a covariance spike); to the extent a real hack retains
a first-order (mean) component, the transition softens from a cliff toward a slope and
$\rho^\star$ becomes the location of steepest descent rather than a true zero. The claim is thus
sharpest for exactly the \emph{obfuscated} hacks that motivate the problem and weakest for clumsy
ones---the useful direction to err. Second, the tax's task-loss slope (retained visible energy
$\mapsto$ forgone reward) is not derived; only its \emph{divergence} is, and the slope is the one
quantity Stage~A.5 calibrates.

\paragraph{The load-bearing constant.} The value of the result rests on the sharp constant of
Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}. We derived it in closed form and matched it to simulation
(\S\ref{sec:results}); the residual risk is empirical, not analytical---whether a real CoT channel
sits in the proportional regime where the $\beta_{\mathrm{sig}}=0$ threshold bites. If it does
not, the result degrades gracefully toward restating a known existence bound, which is why we
mark the boundary rather than paper over it.

\paragraph{Adaptive monitors and co-evolution.} We fix the monitor's subspace $\Smon$; a real
overseer may \emph{re-aim} it during training, projecting onto the directions where the hack
currently lives. This turns the wall into a moving target and the interaction into a dynamic game.
Two remarks bound the effect. First, our result is a per-round statement: at any fixed $\Smon$ the
wall holds, so an adaptive monitor buys time, not immunity---each re-aim resets $\rho$ but the
model re-hides in the new null channel. Second, re-aiming is not free: enlarging the resolved
subspace raises $\alpha$ but, at a fixed labeling budget, lowers the per-direction data budget
$n/d$, which \emph{lowers} $\rho^\star$ (Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}b)---so a monitor that chases the hack across more
directions blinds itself faster on each. The tax argument therefore recurses, and the equilibrium
of the full model-vs-adaptive-monitor game is the natural next object (a Stackelberg version of
Prop.~\ref{prop:selfwall}); \S\ref{sec:results} settles the case where the monitor can aim at the public
task subspace (\S\ref{sec:results}: the wall collapses) and leaves the covering regime open.

\paragraph{Multi-spike (low-rank) hacks.} We model a rank-one hack. A rank-$r$ hack injects spikes
$s_1^2\ge\dots\ge s_r^2$ along orthogonal directions, each with its own null fraction $\rho_i$. The
monitor recovers direction $i$ iff its visible spike clears the edge, $s_i^2(1-\rho_i)>\sqrt\gamma$,
so there is a \emph{per-spike} wall $\rho_i^\star=1-\sqrt\gamma/s_i^2$; the hack is fully hidden once
every spike is sub-critical, and the tax sums the per-spike energy floors. A low-rank hack can thus
keep a few blatant components visible (decoys) while sliding the subtle ones ($s_i^2$ near
$\sqrt\gamma$) below the edge---the multi-spike analogue of obfuscation, and a setting where the
monitor's finite budget $n/d$ must be shared across $r$ directions. The rank-$r$ threshold and the
optimal decoy allocation are a clean extension.

\paragraph{What we do and do not claim.} We claim precisely three things: a \emph{sharp threshold}
$\rho^\star$, a \emph{diverging energy floor} (and, under a positive-slope assumption, a diverging
task tax), and a \emph{geometric pricing unit} for legibility. We do \emph{not} claim that
obfuscation is possible (known~\cite{dewitt,motwani}), that finite oversight distorts objectives
(known~\cite{survey}), or a better monitor. The contribution is orthogonal to all three:
\emph{when} optimization is forced across, and \emph{what} staying legible costs.

\section{Conclusion}
Monitoring fails as a cliff, not a slope. Past a geometry-set pressure $\rho^\star$ the monitor's
recovery overlap with the hack vanishes and no test detects it consistently, the collapse sharpens
as the system grows, and the required visible-energy floor for staying detectable \emph{grows}
without bound in absolute terms---until, once it exceeds the total budget, keeping the model
detectable at target level is infeasible and the monitor is defeated outright. The operational reading is uncomfortable: a monitor reporting healthy AUC is
not holding a safety margin it can spend down, but standing next to a cliff whose edge is invisible
from its own readings. This is what the Monitorability Meter is for---estimating the edge's
\emph{location} and the current distance to it, so an overseer can stop before the wall rather than
discover it afterward.

The result is sharpest for exactly the obfuscated hacks that motivate the problem, and its
real-CoT instantiation---does a language-model trace sit in the regime where the threshold
bites?---is the open empirical question Stages~A.5 and~B are built to answer. Finally, the same
machine ports to the sibling games where a capable optimizer meets an imperfect check: policy
versus reward model (overoptimization onset) and policy versus verifier (coverage). The latter is
worked out in the companion \emph{Coverage Wall} paper, which proves the isomorphism explicitly (its
Lemma~1: coverage $\gamma\leftrightarrow$ resolution $\alpha$, verifier power $\kappa\leftrightarrow$
data budget $n/d$, edge $\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}\leftrightarrow\sqrt{\dmon/n}$) and re-verifies the wall,
converse, game value, and adaptive collapse in coverage notation. The monitoring
wall is the cleanest instance; together they suggest a unified program of \emph{sharp thresholds in
reward hacking}---a critical pressure, a diverging price, and a null channel the optimizer learns to
hide in---whose shared object is exactly that isomorphism, and whose one remaining regime is the
covering game (a task richer than the checker's resolution, the RLVR default), which the core
characterizes as a slope. Making the hiding
spectrum and the monitor's aim endogenous (\S\ref{sec:results}) turns the threshold into a game value---a
critical capability $V^\star$---and sharpens the safety reading: the wall protects the hider only
against a monitor that
cannot aim or is starved of data; an \emph{adaptive} monitor that aims at a \emph{public, coverable}
task subspace and measures its total variance collapses the wall (\S\ref{sec:results}, B1--B4). What remains open is the
one regime where aiming does not suffice---a task subspace larger than the monitor's
budget---whose covering-game value is the program's central conjecture.

\appendix
\section{Reproducibility}\label{app:repro}
All experiments are CPU-only (\texttt{numpy}\,2.4 / \texttt{scipy}\,1.17). \textbf{Code.} Every
figure is generated by a short self-contained script; these, together with a reference
\texttt{numpy} implementation of the Monitorability Meter (the estimators of \S\ref{sec:meter}:
\texttt{null\_channel\_dim}, \texttt{wall\_estimate}, \texttt{monitorability\_price},
\texttt{StoppingRule}) and the gradient-checked tiny transformer, are provided with the submission
and will be released on publication; the Meter is a research reference implementation, not a
hardened library, and
carries the failure modes tabulated in \S\ref{sec:meter}. Detection AUC everywhere uses the same \emph{session
detector}: the monitor estimates $\hat u$ as the top eigenvector of the sample covariance of $n$
projected hack traces, then scores held-out sessions of $b$ traces by mean energy along $\hat u$ and
reports AUC (hack vs.\ clean) over sessions.

\emph{Toy channel (Figs.~\ref{fig:phase}--\ref{fig:twowalls}).} $\alpha=0.5$, $s=1.19$ ($s^2=1.414$), so $\rho^\star=0.50$ at
$n/d=1$. Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}a: $d\in\{100,300,900\}$, $n=d$; session $b=120$, $100$ sessions, $2$ trials. Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}b:
$n/d\in\{0.5,1,2\}$. Fig.~\ref{fig:tax}: tax $=1-\rho_{\max}$ at $\tau=0.72$ vs.\ floor $\sqrt{\alpha/(n/d)}/s^2$.
Fig.~\ref{fig:twowalls}b (converse): $\E_0[L_n^2]=\E_{u,u'}(1-\beta^2\omega^2)^{-n/2}$ ($\omega=\langle\tilde u,\tilde u'\rangle$) Monte-Carlo, $p=6000$,
$4{\times}10^5$ pairs, matching $(1-\beta^2/\gamma)^{-1/2}$ to $3$--$4$ digits below the wall.
Scripts: \texttt{fig1.py, fig2.py, fig3\_two\_walls.py, cgmt\_check.py, converse\_check.py}.

\emph{Effective rank (\S\ref{sec:results}).} With a benign covariance of stable rank
$r_{\mathrm{eff}}$ (whitened within its range), the measured detection wall tracks
$\sqrt{r_{\mathrm{eff}}/n}$: at $\dmon{=}300$, $n{=}400$, generic Haar spike, the wall rises with
$r_{\mathrm{eff}}\in\{50,100,200,300\}$ and meets $\sqrt{\dmon/n}$ at $r_{\mathrm{eff}}{=}\dmon$
(monotone in $r_{\mathrm{eff}}$, a finite-$n$ offset above the exact edge from the AUC$=0.75$
crossing). Script: \texttt{reff\_check.py}.

\emph{Continuous surrogate (Fig.~\ref{fig:surrogate}).} A routing policy $w\in\R^{d}$ is trained (gradient ascent;
verified against the exact arg-max) to maximize an evasion reward minus a quadratic competence cost
of hiding; $\rho=\|P_{\mathrm{mon}}^\perp w\|^2$ emerges. AUC$(\rho)$ from the session detector at
$d_{\mathrm{eval}}=600$; bands are mean$\pm$sd over $24$ seeds; the finite-$d$ transition window
(AUC $0.9\!\to\!0.55$) is $[0.29,0.57]$, bracketing $\rho^\star$ and narrowing as $d^{-1/3}$. Tax
slope $\kappa=1.9\pm1.2$ (reward $=2(1-\text{AUC})$, slope at the wall over seeds). Script:
\texttt{fig4\_ci.py}.

\emph{Token transformer (Fig.~\ref{fig:token}).} A single-layer causal self-attention policy (\texttt{numpy},
manual backprop, gradient check max rel.\ err.\ $4{\times}10^{-7}$): $d_{\mathrm{model}}=16$,
vocabulary $48$, CoT length $8$. Trained by REINFORCE (Adam, lr $0.015$, batch $64$, running-mean
baseline, $\sim\!900$ episodes) from a $\lambda{=}0$ pre-trained init. The CoT readout direction
$w=\mathrm{normalize}(\sum_t E_{\mathrm{out}}[\text{tok}_t])$ is the injected spike; the spike
magnitude $s^2=1.414$ is fixed (controlled SNR); reward $=\langle w,v\rangle^2-\lambda\,
\sigma(\kappa(s^2\|P_{\mathrm{mon}}w\|^2-\text{edge}))$ with $v$ mostly visible; monitor budget
$n=d=40$. Points are mean$\pm$sd over $3$ seeds; the small $d{=}40$ leaves the AUC collapse
finite-size-broad (cf.\ Fig.~\ref{fig:phase}a). Scripts: \texttt{tt\_model.py, tt\_spike.py, tt\_ci.py}.

\emph{Two-time-scale dynamics (\S\ref{sec:results}, core simulations).} Slow policy
$\rho_k$ / fast monitor $\hat D_k$ stochastic approximation, $a_k=0.03/(1{+}k/400)^{0.6}$,
$b_k=0.30/(1{+}k/400)^{0.51}$ ($a_k/b_k\to0$); fast variable tracks the BBP detectability
$D^\star(\rho)$ with estimation noise $1/\sqrt n$ ($n{=}200$); slow variable ascends
$J=\lambda(1{-}D^\star)-0.9\rho$ with SGD noise $0.15$; $16$ seeds. The converged $\rho_\infty$ meets
$\rho^\star{=}0.50$ once past the barrier; the metastable band is where the hidden basin is the
global optimum but the SA is still trapped visible. Script: \texttt{twotimescale.py}.

\section{Self-contained core: the wall and converse, in monitoring notation}\label{app:selfcontained}
For self-containedness we restate the two load-bearing results---the wall and its converse---and sketch
their proof in monitoring notation, so this paper's central claim stands without the core paper. (It is
the same BBP/CGMT argument; full proofs and the game/saturation/adaptive results are in~\cite{core}.)

\paragraph{Setup, recalled.} An obfuscated hack injects a variance spike of energy $s^2$ along a unit
direction $u\in\R^d$; the monitor resolves an $\dmon=\alpha d$-dimensional subspace and estimates $u$
from $n$ traces. Under pressure $\rho$ it routes a fraction $\rho$ into the null channel, leaving a
visible spike $\beta=s^2(1-\rho)$; write $\gamma=\dmon/n$.

\begin{proposition}[Monitoring wall + converse, self-contained]\label{prop:selfwall}
In the proportional regime $\dmon,n\to\infty$ with $\dmon/n\to\gamma$: \emph{(i)} the recovery overlap
is $\langle\hat u,u\rangle^2\to\big[(1-\gamma/\beta^2)/(1+\gamma/\beta)\big]_+$, positive iff
$\beta>\sqrt\gamma$, i.e.\ zero iff $\rho\ge\rho^\star=[1-\sqrt\gamma/s^2]_0^1$; \emph{(ii)} for
$\beta<\sqrt\gamma$ the clean and hacked trace laws are contiguous, the likelihood-ratio second moment
$\E_0[L_n^2]\to(1-\beta^2/\gamma)^{-1/2}<\infty$, so no test of the $n$ projected traces detects the
hack consistently. The two thresholds coincide.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof sketch.} The projected traces have population covariance
$I_{\dmon}+\beta\,\tilde u\tilde u^\top$ ($\tilde u$ the unit visible component). By BBP the top sample
eigenvalue leaves the Marchenko--Pastur bulk iff $\beta>\sqrt\gamma$, with eigenvector overlap as in
(i); below the edge the overlap is $0$ and any statistic built from $\hat u$ is asymptotically
uninformative. Since $\beta=s^2(1-\rho)$, the edge is crossed at $\rho^\star$. For (ii), the single-spike
Le~Cam second moment with a uniform prior on $u$ is $(1-\beta^2/\gamma)^{-1/2}$, finite iff
$\beta<\sqrt\gamma$; a bounded second moment gives contiguity, hence no consistent test. The sharp
constant follows from the CGMT fixed point $\Phi_{\mathrm{AO}}(\mu)=\sqrt{\gamma(1-\mu^2)}+\sqrt{1+\beta\mu^2}$,
whose $\mu=0$/nontrivial-branch bifurcation at $\beta=\sqrt\gamma$ reproduces both (i) and the
Marchenko--Pastur edge~\cite{core}. \hfill$\square$

